title.narrative: Commonwealth Finance Minister’s Meeting (CFMM) and G20 Outreach

description.narrative:
The Commonwealth’s hosting of CFMM, and meetings related to CFMM (meeting of Central Bank Governors and Senior Finance Ministry Officials) and the Commonwealth-G20 meetings intend to bring together different views of the most influential Ministries and economic bodies in the Association, and to allow for a dialogue with the world’s most influential decision-making body. The project seeks to address the lack of consensus amongst Commonwealth countries, particularly between Commonwealth G20 and developing countries, on challenging and important economic issues. A consensus on these issues allows the Commonwealth to contribute materially to the international financing for development agenda, which underpins the success of the SDGs. The project will address the problem and deliver to this cross cutting outcome through a reform of CFMM to integrate G20 discussions, discuss the Annual Report on Commonwealth Economic Interconnectivity and pursue a closer collaboration with the Chair and countries. This approach is expected to result in a selection of topics which have global Commonwealth interest including COVID-19 related issues, and which create greater opportunities for consensus-building. The Secretariat’s value-added is rooted in its ability to table difficult issues and to gain member country consensus, a feat that is not achievable in most other forums.
In addition, there are annual meetings for small states intended to promote the international recognition of their vulnerabilities and development needs. These are the Global Biennial Conference on Small States (GBCSS) and the Commonwealth Ministers Meetings on Small States (CMMSS). The CMMSS is held in the margins of CHOGM as a platform for the Ministers to consider and agree on concrete actions to advance the development priorities of small states with a view to up scale global response to their developmental needs.
The achievement of this cross cutting outcome is expected to support economic development for developing countries, in particular, small states at the time when countries are recovering from the effects of COVID-19 pandemic .
